<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="section-label">How it works</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">From PR history to trusted rules — with receipts</h2>
    <p class="section-body">
      RepoMind doesn't just ask an LLM to "write engineering guidelines."
      It mines your actual review history, clusters patterns, scores
      specificity, and demands human approval before anything ships.
    </p>

    <div class="pipeline-steps">
      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <div class="pipeline-number">1</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Ingest</h3>
          <p>
            Fetch PRs, review threads, comments, and diff hunks via the
            GitHub GraphQL API. Every thread carries resolution status —
            was the feedback accepted or pushed back on?
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <div class="pipeline-number">2</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Extract</h3>
          <p>
            LLM reads each review thread and identifies candidate lessons.
            Filters out one-off nitpicks, bot comments, and obvious
            best-practices any LLM already knows.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <div class="pipeline-number">3</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Cluster</h3>
          <p>
            "Use eager loading." "Avoid N+1." "Missing with()." → one rule,
            63 occurrences, 5 reviewers. Embeddings group similar feedback
            across years of PRs.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <div class="pipeline-number">4</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Score</h3>
          <p>
            Each candidate is scored on specificity (team-specific vs.
            generic), consensus (multi-reviewer, low contradiction), and
            recency. "92% confidence" has a defined meaning — not a vibe.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pipeline-step">
        <div class="pipeline-number">5</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Approve &amp; Export</h3>
          <p>
            A human reviews before anything ships. Approved rules render into
            CLAUDE.md, .cursor/rules, copilot-instructions, and more — kept
            in sync as the knowledge base evolves.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
